    <h2>Heathmont — Quiet Residential Enclave, 1960s–1970s Homes, High Fireplace Rate</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Heathmont is a quieter residential suburb tucked between Ringwood and Bayswater, developed mainly through the 1960s and 1970s on relatively flat to gently undulating terrain. Despite its modest size, Heathmont has an unusually high rate of homes with original solid-fuel heating systems — the suburb was built during the era when open fireplaces and early slow-combustion heaters were standard inclusions in new homes, and a large number of these installations remain in active use today. The housing stock is predominantly solid brick veneer, and the chimney stacks on these properties are typically original brick construction from the 1960s or 1970s. After 50-plus years of seasonal use, these chimneys frequently show signs of mortar deterioration, especially around the chimney crown and the mortar joints in the upper section of the stack. Creosote buildup from decades of wood burning is also a consistent finding in Heathmont properties — particularly in homes that have burned unseasoned or mixed timber over the years. Heathmont sits close to the Dandenong Ranges foothills, and while it doesn't have the elevation of suburbs further east, it still experiences a colder winter character than Melbourne's inner suburbs. Cold southerly airflows are funnelled along the flat valley sections, and overnight frosts are common from May through August. We service Heathmont as part of our eastern Melbourne corridor run and are very familiar with the older chimney configurations typical of the suburb.</p></div>
